<CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Great America's new ride: the Vortex, a $5.5 million
stand-up roller coaster.; PHOTO: The Flying Karamazov Brothers will be
performing at Stanford on Friday.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  CHILDREN; FAMILY; ENTERTAINMENT; RECREATION; LIST  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  A DAY of family fun is set from 1 p.m. to 4 p.m. today at the Triton Museum of
Art, 1505 Warburton Ave., Santa Clara, to celebrate the opening of an exhibit
of artwork by students in the Santa Clara Unified School District.
Storytellers and puppeteers will perform and there will be hands-on art
activities for the kids and refreshments. The exhibit features artwork from
kindergarten through the 12th grade and will continue on display through April
14. Other exhibits at the museum are "Raymond Lark: Artist of Tradition and
Diversity," "Eagle Mountain: Jeff Lipshutz and John Huddleston," a pictorial
story of a California ghost town and "New Works by California Artists." (408)
247-3754.;    (box) Vortex,  the new $5.5 million stand-up roller coaster,
joins major attractions at Great America theme park this weekend to open the
park's 15th season. The looping, twisting, steel stand-up roller coaster is
the only one of its kind west of the Mississippi. The ride has more than 1,920
feet of track, climbs 91 feet and reaches a top speed (in descent) of 45 mph.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  AN ARTFUL FAMILY OUTING  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Family Clipboard
Things to do  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Also premiering at Great America this weekend is "Blue Planet," the latest
IMAX film. Presented by the Smithsonian Institution's National Air and Space
Museum and Lockheed Corp. in cooperation with the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration, the 42-minute film provides a living atlas -- a moving
portrait -- of the planet Earth. The movie explores the balance of life on
Earth and various forces such as storms, volcanoes, earthquakes and
humankind.;    The park opens at 10 a.m. today and weekends only through May
26. It is located at Great America Parkway between highways 101 and 237, Santa
Clara. Admission is $20.95 adults, $13.95 seniors, 55 and over and $10.45
children 3-6. Call (408) 988-1776 for details.;    (box) More than 3,500 dogs
(representing 16 breeds) will gather today for the final day in one of the
largest dog shows in the Bay Area. The show opens at 8 a.m. and runs through
the late afternoon at the Alameda County Fairgrounds, 4501 Pleasanton Ave.,
Pleasanton. It is sponsored by the Del Valle Dog Club of Livermore and Kalkan
dog food. Sanctioned by the American Kennel Club, the show will feature the
debut of the newest AKC breed, the Petit Basset Vendeen Griffon. Admission is
$4 adults, $2 children with a maximum of $10 per family. Parking is $3.;   
Other family activities this week include:; ENTERTAINMENT; "Alice"  will be
given by the Star-Brite Children's Theater at American High Theater, 36300
Fremont Blvd., Fremont. Times are 3 p.m. and 7:30 p.m. Saturday and 3 and 7:30
p.m. March 23. Tickets are $5. Call (415) 791-5841. Star-Brite Children's
Theater is funded by Fremont Adult School and is in its sixth year.;    "The
Carnival of the Animals"  and "The Story of Babar," a production of the Mills
College Children's School, will feature Roy Bogas on piano and Scott Beach,
radio personality, at 3 p.m. today in Haas Pavilion, Mills College, 5000
MacArthur Blvd., Oakland. Nancy Estrick will create drawings on stage as each
animal is musically presented. The spring concert is a benefit for the
Children's School Scholarship Fund. Tickets are $8 adults and $5 children.
Bogas' arrangement of Camille Saint-Saens' composition "The Carnival of the
Animals" has been used for many years to introduce children to classical
music. For details call (415) 430-3169.;    The Flying Karamazov Brothers 
bring their "Theater of the Air" to Memorial Auditorium at Stanford University
at 8 p.m. Friday. The brothers, all with Bay Area connections, combine music
and quips with their program. One feature of their program, "The Gamble,"
dares the audience to give the troupe's champ, "Ivan," anything under 10
pounds, over one ounce and smaller than a bread box to juggle. Ivan gets three
tries to juggle to the count of 10. If he succeeds, the brothers get a
standing ovation; if he fails, he gets a pie in the face. Ivan, incidentally,
received a bachelor's degree in biology from UC-Santa Cruz before joining the
brothers. Tickets are $16-$22, $13-$19 students. Call (408) 998-2277, (415)
762-2277.; EXHIBITS; Dinosaurs return.  Eight robotic dinosaurs in prehistoric
settings are being shown through May 27 at UC-Berkeley's Lawrence Hall of
Science. There is a Paleo Pit, where you can do dinosaur puzzles, games and
touch a real dinosaur bone. The live musical, "Dino Doesn't Live Here
Anymore," is a feature of the exhibit. Admission is $2-$4. The facility is
located on Centennial Drive, below Grizzly Peak Boulevard, Berkeley. For
details, call (415) 642-5133.;    "Where in the World"  is the title of the
current exhibit in Palo Alto on geography, featuring hands-on activities, maps
and map making and old navigational equipment. Hours are 10 a.m.-5 p.m.
Tuesdays-Saturdays and 1-4 p.m. Sundays at the Palo Alto Junior Museum and
Zoo, 1451 Middlefield Road, Palo Alto. The exhibit runs through March 31.
Free. (415) 329-2111.; UPCOMING; "Maggie Magalita"  This original play will be
presented by the California Theater Center in Spanish and English at 11 a.m.
Saturdays, March 30 and April 5 at the Community Center, 550 E. Remington
Drive, Sunnyvale. "Maggie Magalita" is about the struggle of an adolescent
girl attempting to understand and honor her Hispanic traditions while trying
to gain the acceptance of her modern American peers. The play is appropriate
for grades 4 and up. Tickets are $7 advance, $8 at the door. For details, call
(408) 245-2978.  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  DOROTHY PRIES, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE>
